'''John Richard Clark Hall''' (1855 – 6 August 1931) was a scholar of [[Old English]], notable for his work on ''[[Beowulf]]''. In 1894 he published a dictionary of Anglo-Saxon words,{{sfn|Hausmann|Reichmann|Weigand|Zgusta|1990|p=1443}} which he followed up with complete verse and metrical translations of the poem.{{sfn|Osborn|2014}} His 1901 translation was the tenth to be published in English; a metrical translation followed in 1914,{{sfn|Hall|1914}} and in 1940 was edited by [[Charles Leslie Wrenn]].{{sfn|Osborn|2014}}

==Career==
John Richard Clark Hall was born in 1855,{{sfn|Hausmann|Reichmann|Weigand|Zgusta|1990}} and achieved both a [[Master of Arts]] and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]].{{sfn|The Scotsman|1931}}

Hall published two translations of the [[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo-Saxon]] epic poem ''[[Beowulf]]'',{{sfn|Osborn|2014}} in addition to multiple editions of ''A Concise Anglo-Saxon Dictionary''.{{sfn|Hausmann|Reichmann|Weigand|Zgusta|1990}} His first edition of the dictionary was published in 1894, and attempted to ease access by ordering entries by the words as they were actually spelled in common editions of [[Old English]] texts.{{sfn|Hausmann|Reichmann|Weigand|Zgusta|1990}} As Hall himself acknowledged in the second edition that followed in 1916, however, this "was admittedly an unscientific [approach], and opened the door to a good many errors and inconsistencies".{{sfn|Hall|1916|p=v}} With the second edition he adopted the conventional method of using "normalised" entry words.{{sfn|Hausmann|Reichmann|Weigand|Zgusta|1990}} A third edition followed in 1931, a reprinting with a supplement by Herbert Dean Meritt came in 1960, and this was itself reprinted in 1984.{{sfn|Hausmann|Reichmann|Weigand|Zgusta|1990}}

In 1910, after publication of the first edition of his dictionary, Hall published a literal translation of ''Beowulf''.{{sfn|Osborn|2014}} It was the tenth [[English language|English]] translation of the work; the eighth, in 1892, had also been translated by a John Hall, [[John Lesslie Hall]].{{sfn|Osborn|2014}} He followed this up four years later with another translation, this time in [[Metre (poetry)|metre]].{{sfn|Osborn|2014}} In 1940, after Hall's death, his prose translation was revised by [[Charles Leslie Wrenn]], and again in 1950;{{sfn|Osborn|2014}} this latter edition included a preface by [[J. R. R. Tolkien]].{{sfn|Hall|1950}}

Hall died in 1931.{{sfn|The Scotsman|1931}} He had been living in [[Eastbourne]] in [[East Sussex]].{{sfn|The Scotsman|1931}} His obituary labeled him a "protestant reformer", noted that he had formerly been on the Local Government Board in [[Whitehall]], and that he had a net [[Personal property|personalty]] of £13,309 and a gross of £15,762.{{sfn|The Scotsman|1931}}

