{{Infobox historic site|name=Meyazia 27 Square|native_name=ሜያአዚያ 27 ካሬ|native_language=am|image=File:Arat Kilo Monument.JPG|image_size=200px|location=[[Addis Ababa]], [[Ethiopia]]|built=1930|demolished=1936, 1974|restored=1990s}}
'''Meyazia 27 Square''' ({{Lang-am|ሜያአዚያ 27 ካሬ}}; commonly called "Arat Kilo") is an important and historic intersection and surrounding neighborhood in Addis Ababa, located where Adwa St, King George VI St, Queen Elizabeth II St, and Development Through Cooperation Ave come together. Its name denotes both the day when Addis Ababa [[March of the Iron Will|fell to Italy]] in 1936 and was [[East African Campaign (World War II)#The liberation of Addis Ababa|liberated]] in 1941.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Heart of Ethiopia|last=Forbes|first=Duncan|publisher=|year=1972|isbn=|location=|pages=17}}</ref> The park is under the aegis of the Addis Ababa Land Development and Urban Renewal Agency.

Many buildings of the [[Government of Ethiopia|Ethiopian government]] and [[Addis Ababa University]] are near the square.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Haile Sellassie's students: the intellectual and social background to revolution, 1952-1977|last=Balsvik|first=Randi Rønning|publisher=|year=1985|isbn=|location=|pages=22}}</ref> The eastern side of the square is dominated by the [[Ministry of Education (Ethiopia)|Ministry of Education]], the western side has Addis Ababa University Department of Computer Science and the Archaeology Museum. Among the heterogeneous assortment adjacent buildings are the [[Holy Trinity Cathedral (Addis Ababa)|Holy Trinity Cathedral]], [[Ethiopian Parliament Building|Parliament building]], and [[Menelik Palace|Imperial Palace Building]].

== History ==
Meyazia 27 Square is noted for its impressive obelisk built for ''Atse'' Haile Selassie's coronation in 1930.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Antonsich|first=Marco|date=2001|title=Signs of power: Fascist urban iconographies in Ethiopia (1930s–1940s)|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/academia.edu.documents/30316391/Antonsich_Ethiopia.pdf?AWSAccessKeyId=AKIAIWOWYYGZ2Y53UL3A&Expires=1538893690&Signature=jAIG3nA%2BMw0tc2A6SFQYVSrxGEo%3D&response-content-disposition=inline%3B%20filename%3DSigns_of_power_Fascist_urban_iconographi.pdf|journal=GeoJournal|volume=52|pages=325–338|via=}}</ref> The historic moment depicts a Lion of Judah and a circle of relief figures and monumental panels celebrating the liberation of Ethiopia. In 1936, during the occupation of Ethiopia by [[Kingdom of Italy|Fascist Italy]], the monument was removed. Following the liberation of Ethiopia, the monument was rebuilt. After the [[Ethiopian Revolution]], the [[Derg]] removed the relief of the Emperor Haile Selassie from the monument. After the end of the Ethiopian Civil War, the monument was restored.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.angelfire.com/ny/ethiocrown/monuments.html|title=Imperial Monuments of Ethiopia|last=|first=|date=|work=Imperial Ethiopia|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|accessdate=22 August 2013}}</ref>

